{{Accessory | Name=TurboTap | Guid=3000-50 | Deck=Multiplayer accessory for the TurboGrafx-16 and PC Engine. | Image=https://www.giantbomb.com/a/uploads/scale_super/18/185326/2505550-0335083823-nec-t.jpg}}
<div id='imageData' data-json='{"infobox":{"file":"2505550-0335083823-nec-t.jpg","path":"18\/185326\/","mime":"image\/jpeg","sizes":"scale_tiny,square_small,square_tiny,square_medium,scale_super,square_mini,scale_avatar,scale_small,scale_large,scale_medium,screen_medium,square_avatar,screen_kubrick","caption":""},"background":[]}' />
==Overview== The [[Platforms/TurboGrafx_16|TurboGrafx-16]] console is provisioned for one controller. The TurboTap accessory plugs into the game port, thereby allowing up to five simultaneous players, in games specifically designed for it. The TurboTap was released in 1989 with an MSRP of $17.99. Games supporting the TurboTap do so in varying degrees. Some allow simultaneous five-player gameplay, while others simply allow two player alternating gameplay, without the necessity of sharing a controller. The following games support the TurboTap: * [[Games/1943_Kai_Midway_Kaisen|1943 Kai]] * [[Games/Bomberman_1983|Bomberman]] * [[Games/Cadash|Cadash]] * [[Games/Devils_Crush|Devil's Crush]] * [[Games/Dungeon_Explorer|Dungeon Explorer]] * [[Games/Fantasy_Zone|Fantasy Zone]] * [[Games/Final_Lap_Twin|Final Lap Twin]] * [[Games/King_of_Casino|King of Casino]] * [[Games/Mega_Bomberman|Mega Bomberman]] * [[Games/Moto_Roader|Moto Roader]] * [[Games/Moto_Roader_II|Moto Roader II]] * [[Games/Ninja_Spirit|Ninja Spirit]] * [[Games/Pac_Land|Pac-Land]] * [[Panza Kick Boxing|Panza Kick Boxing]] * [[Games/Parasol_Stars_The_Story_of_Bubble_Bobble_III|Parasol Stars]] * [[Games/Super_Soccer|Super Soccer]] * [[Games/Super_Volleyball|Super Volleyball]] * [[Games/TV_Sports_Basketball|TV Sports: Basketball]] * [[Games/TV_Sports_Football|TV Sports: Football]] The PC Engine's multitap, and the TurboDuo's DuoTap are identical to that of the TurboGrafx-16, save for a white case rather than black.

{{Accessory | Name=Wii Wheel | Guid=3000-7 | Deck=The Wii Wheel is a plastic shell that makes using the Wii Remote feel more like a steering wheel. The Wii Wheel was packaged with Mario Kart Wii and could also be bought separately. | Image=https://www.giantbomb.com/a/uploads/scale_super/0/2009/192808-41ddcylhvsl1.jpg}}
<div id='imageData' data-json='{"infobox":{"file":"192808-41ddcylhvsl1.jpg","path":"0\/2009\/","mime":"image\/jpeg","sizes":"scale_medium,scale_super,square_mini,square_medium,square_small,screen_medium,square_avatar,scale_small,scale_large,scale_avatar,square_tiny,screen_kubrick","caption":""},"background":[]}' /> The Wii Wheel is an add-on for the [[Accessories/Wii_Remote|Wii Remote]], intended for use with racing games that use a sideways "steering wheel" configuration. It does not add any functionality to the Wii Remote, but tries to recreate the feel of holding a real steering wheel. It has a hole on the back to pass the wrist strap and one on its left to avoid any interference between the controller and the Wii.
The Wii Wheel is available as part of the [[Games/Mario_Kart_Wii|Mario Kart Wii]] package, and can also be purchased separately. Although originally designed and packaged for use with Mario Kart Wii, it works with most Wii racing games that only require the Wii Remote to be held sideways to play. There are other Wii steerring wheels out there made by third party companies but the Wii Wheel is the official Nintendo product

{{Accessory | Name=Wii Zapper | Guid=3000-15 | Deck=The Wii Zapper is a peripheral that transforms the Wiimote and Nunchuk into a gun shape. | Image=https://www.giantbomb.com/a/uploads/scale_super/0/25/10945-ninoaye9.jpg}}
<div id='imageData' data-json='{"infobox":{"file":"10945-ninoaye9.jpg","path":"0\/25\/","mime":"image\/jpeg","sizes":"scale_medium,scale_super,square_mini,square_medium,square_small,screen_medium,square_avatar,scale_small,scale_large,scale_avatar,square_tiny,screen_kubrick","caption":"Final design of the Wii Zapper"},"background":[]}' />
==Overview== The Wii Zapper is a plastic shell for the [[Accessories/Wii_Remote|Wii Remote]] and Nunchuk designed to emulate the shape of a gun while retaining usability. Development on the Zapper began informally when a Nintendo employee working on [http://dev.giantbomb.com:8080/the-legend-of-zelda-twilight-princess/61-19467 The Legend of Zelda: Twilight Princess] fabricated a frame for the Wii Remote and Nunchuk out of wires and rubber bands. [http://dev.giantbomb.com:8080/shigeru-miyamoto/72-614 Shigeru Miyamoto] was initially upset by what appeared to be a waste of time, though when he held it, he found it surprisingly comfortable. When the Zapper was first shown to the public at E3 2006, its shape was similar to that of a [[Objects/Shotgun|shotgun]], but by E3 2007 the design was altered to appear more like a [[Objects/Submachine_Gun|submachine gun]]. The Wii Zapper was released in America on November 19, 2007, and was initially supported by [[Games/Resident_Evil_The_Umbrella_Chronicles|Resident Evil: The Umbrella Chronicles]], [[Games/Ghost_Squad|Ghost Squad]], [[Games/Medal_of_Honor_Heroes_2|Medal of Honor: Heroes 2]], and [[Games/Links_Crossbow_Training|Link's Crossbow Training]].

{{Accessory | Name=neGcon | Guid=3000-33 | Deck=The Namco neGcon is an analog steering controller that allows each half to be twisted. Released for the PlayStation, it was also compatible with a limited number of PlayStation 2 releases. | Image=https://www.giantbomb.com/a/uploads/scale_super/0/56/678882-namco_negcon_centred.jpg}}
<div id='imageData' data-json='{"infobox":{"file":"678882-namco_negcon_centred.jpg","path":"0\/56\/","mime":"image\/jpeg","sizes":"square_avatar,square_small,scale_small,screen_medium,scale_large,scale_avatar,square_mini,scale_medium,square_tiny,square_medium,scale_super,scale_tiny,screen_kubrick","caption":""},"background":[]}' />
==Overview== The NeGcon (pronounced "Neh-Gee-Con") is a third-party controller manufactured by Namco in 1995 for the [[Platforms/PlayStation|Sony Playstation]]. This unique controller consisted of two halves connected by a swivel joint. Each half could be twisted relative to the other. This twisting motion registered as a directional command and served as a replacement for the analog sticks featured on Sony's DualShock controller. The goal of the NeGcon was to afford racing game enthusiasts precision steering controls. In addition to swivel controls, the NeGcon also featured a unique button layout. The R2, L2 and select buttons are not present on the NeGcon. The lack of R2 and L2 was likely due to many popular racing games on the Playstation mapping acceleration and brake to face buttons instead of shoulder buttons. Buttons required a larger than average travel distance before being activated. Namco intended for the NeGcon to be held in a similar fashion to that of a steering wheel. You could hold the NeGcon with your fingers forming a fist, while your thumbs hovered over the face of the controller. Use of the NeGcon was supported by many racing games such as [[Franchises/Gran_Turismo|Gran Turismo]], [[Games/Destruction_Derby|Destruction Derby]], the [[Franchises/Ridge_Racer|Ridge Racer series]] and the [[Franchises/WipEout|WipeOut series]]. Though the controller was intended solely for use with the Playstation, some [[Platforms/PlayStation_2|Playstation 2]] games such as [[Games/WipEout_Fusion|WipeOut Fusion]] and [[Games/Ridge_Racer_V|Ridge Racer V]] also featured support. The[[Franchises/Ace_Combat|Ace Combat series]] is one of the very few examples of non-racing games that allow the use of the NeGcon. The NeGcon saw very little success in the third-party controller market, presumably due to limited compatibility and odd design. However, the device still holds some monetary value due to its rarity and hobbyist/collectors interest.
